PSR J0002+6216 is a normal pulsar with a period of 115.36 milliseconds and has a fairly large dispersion measure of 218.6 pc/cc. It is an extremely faint pulsar with a 1400 MHz catalogue flux density of 22.0 microJy. PSR J0002+6216 is a Northern Hemisphere pulsar with an associated gamma-ray source (4FGL_J0002.8+6217) and an associated x-ray source (1XSPS_J000257.6+621609). This pulsar has a period derivative of 5.97e-15. PSR J0002+6216 has a typical slow pulsar-like magnetic field strength of 8.40e+11 G. The distance to J0002+6216 is 6 kpc. This pulsar appears to be solitary. PSR J0002+6216 was discovered in 2017 as part of the Fermi Gamma-ray Observatory blind survey.

PSR J0633-2015 was discovered in 2006 as part of the Parkes high-latitude multibeam pulsar survey.

It has a typical slow pulsar-like magnetic field strength of 2.98e+12 G. PSR J0837+0610 has an intermediate transverse velocity of 46 km/s. The distance to J0837+0610 is 0 kpc. This pulsar appears to be solitary. PSR J0837+0610 was discovered in 1968 as part of a minor survey.

PSR J1431-5740 has a fairly typical orbital period of 2.727 days and a very circular orbit with an eccentricity of 4.300e-06. It is an ancient pulsar with an age of 10 Gyr. PSR J1431-5740 has a low magnetic field strength of 1.64e+08 G. The distance to J1431-5740 is 4 kpc. This pulsar has a low-mass companion with a minimum mass of 0.156 solar masses. PSR J1431-5740 was discovered in 2013 as part of the Parkes High Time Resolution Universe survey (HTRU).

PSR J1504-5621 is a middle-aged pulsar with an age of 1 Myr. It has a typical slow pulsar-like magnetic field strength of 1.53e+12 G. The distance to J1504-5621 is 4 kpc. This pulsar appears to be solitary. PSR J1504-5621 was discovered in 2003 as part of the Parkes multibeam pulsar survey.
